<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-exploring-distributions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title></title>
   <example>
    <title>Example: Exploring Different Distributions Using the Skulls Data</title>
    <p>
      The skulls dataset introduced earlier in this chapter can also be used to explore different probability distributions. 
      Although the observed number of skulls follows a Binomial model, the <em>Show Model</em> dialog allows you to investigate 
      how the same values relate to other theoretical distributions.
    </p>
    <p>
      Load the skulls dataset and open the <em>Show Model</em> dialog. 
      Select the <em>Values</em> output option and choose each of the following distributions in turn:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Normal
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>t</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Chi-square
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>F</m>
          </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      For each distribution, experiment with different parameter values and compare the resulting graphs. 
      Notice how changing the parameters affects the location, spread and shape of the distribution. 
      Although the skulls data were generated from a Binomial experiment, this exercise demonstrates how 
      different probability models can be explored using a common interface in R-Instat.
    </p>
  </example>

  <p>
    In the following chapters we will make extensive use of these distributions when carrying out hypothesis tests, 
    confidence intervals and analysis of variance. At this stage it is not necessary to understand every mathematical 
    relationship between them. Instead, focus on recognising their shapes, understanding the role of their parameters and becoming 
    familiar with exploring them using the <em>Show Model</em> dialog in R-Instat.
  </p>
</subsection>